                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.51/111.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">French Ambassador</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-02-11">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 11, 1915</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Ambassador</hi>: Referring to the Department’s
                    note No. 1449, of February 4, 1915, relative to a report that the Carrancista
                    forces at Vera Cruz have seized 500 rifles and a certain quantity of cartridges
                    which were stored in the custom house at Vera Cruz, belonging to the French
                    Government, I beg to inform you that the Department is in receipt of a telegram
                    from the American Consul at Vera Cruz, dated February 8, stating that these
                    munitions of war <pb facs="1176" n="1060" xml:id="pg_1060"/> have been
                    confiscated, notwithstanding a promise made to the French Consul that the return
                    of the shipment to France would be permitted.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">W. J. Bryan.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
